    "pathophysiology": "Three immune mechanisms: (1) Hapten type: the drug binds covalently to the RBC membrane and acts as a hapten; antibodies (usually IgG) bind to the drug-RBC complex, leading to extravascular splenic clearance. (2) Immune complex type: the drug forms a complex with circulating antibody; the drug-antibody immune complex adsorbs non-specifically to the RBC surface, activating complement and causing predominantly intravascular hemolysis. (3) Autoantibody induction: the drug (e.g. methyldopa) alters immune regulation, causing production of true anti-RBC autoantibodies (anti-Rh specificity) that persist even after drug withdrawal for weeks to months.",
